+{"id":"bd-yr8d","title":"Three-lane scheduler: prevent cancel lane monopoly","description":"# Bug: Cancel Lane Monopoly Causes Ready Work Starvation

## Location
`src/runtime/scheduler/three_lane.rs:204-208`

## Issue Description

The main loop prioritizes cancel work without bounds:

```rust
// PHASE 1: Cancel work (highest priority, never starve)
if let Some(task) = self.try_cancel_work() {
    self.execute(task);
    continue;  // Loop back, tries cancel again immediately
}
```

The comment says "never starve" but that refers to cancel work - 
the ready lane CAN be starved by continuous cancel work.

## Starvation Scenario

```
Time    Cancel Queue    Ready Queue    Executed
────    ────────────    ───────────    ────────
0       [C1]            [R1, R2]       C1
1       [C2] (new)      [R1, R2]       C2
2       [C3] (new)      [R1, R2]       C3
...     ...             [R1, R2]       ...
N       []              [R1, R2]       R1 (finally!)
```

If tasks continuously reschedule themselves to the cancel lane 
(e.g., rapid cancellation cascade), ready work waits indefinitely.

## Impact

- **Severity**: MEDIUM (fairness violation)
- **Exploitability**: Triggered by cancel-heavy workloads
- **Impact**: Ready tasks experience unbounded latency

## Root Cause

The scheduler lacks a fairness bound on consecutive cancel executions.
While cancel work IS higher priority, it shouldn't completely starve 
other lanes.

## Proposed Fix

Add a fairness counter that limits consecutive cancel executions:

```rust
const MAX_CONSECUTIVE_CANCEL: usize = 16;

fn run_loop(&mut self) {
    let mut consecutive_cancel = 0;

    loop {
        // PHASE 1: Cancel work (with fairness limit)
        if consecutive_cancel < MAX_CONSECUTIVE_CANCEL {
            if let Some(task) = self.try_cancel_work() {
                self.execute(task);
                consecutive_cancel += 1;
                continue;
            }
        }

        // PHASE 2: Ready work (resets cancel counter)
        if let Some(task) = self.try_ready_work() {
            self.execute(task);
            consecutive_cancel = 0;  // Reset after ready work
            continue;
        }

        // PHASE 3: Timed work
        if let Some(task) = self.try_timed_work() {
            self.execute(task);
            consecutive_cancel = 0;
            continue;
        }

        // Reset counter when going idle
        consecutive_cancel = 0;
        // ... backoff/park logic
    }
}
```

## Alternative: Weighted Fair Queuing

Instead of hard limit, use weighted scheduling:
- Cancel: weight 4
- Ready: weight 2  
- Timed: weight 1

